\I still don't understand it myself.

\Other corrections, I must admit, should not have been necessary; even I know that it
\should be "del evento" and not "de la evento". I'm learning. But I will probably make that
\same kind of mistake again.
Yes I know Gerry but for you to read the correct form and for us to read it well.

\Here are some of the other changes/improvements that have already been implemented:

Wow! \- "de" is allowed in names if "de" is not followed by an article, for example "el error de e/s".
So good! \- i/o error messages are now in Spanish; the global variable "i/o error" is now called "error de e/s".
Fine. \- "A spot" is now "un punto" instead of "un foco".
Really good! Si el trabajo no está completo, salir. \- "Nay sayers" (I like that term) can now be called using "no" BEFORE the verb, for example "Si el trabajo no es completa, salir."
Good option for many Spanish speakers. \- Decider routines can be terminated with "diga si" or "diga no" or just "di no".
\- New local variables can be created "on the fly" when setting a field, for example "Poner 15 mm en la coordenada-y de un punto." (which creates a new local variable of type punto)
Watch out: objetivo w/o "c", lost ages ago. "Paradero" a beautiful word. \- The special, hard-coded fields (target, magnitude and whereabouts) now have Spanish names (objectivo, magnitud, paradero).
Ok. \- The keywords for loops are now "LAZO, INTERRUMPTIR, SALIR, and REPETIR."
Ok. \- All the general-purpose Spanish types, globals, and routine headers needed by the Sal Monet have been integrated into the 1008 el seso.
Fine. Superlatives for future SAL or added by programmer. \- The simplified color names have been implemented
Not bad. \- The routine that quits a program (and the button that quits the Sal Monet) are both now called "Abandonar", matching the command under the "A" menu.
Ok. \- "Mayúsculas Todo" and "Minúsculas Todo" now appear after "Mayúscula Inicial" on the "M"  menu.

\I'm waiting for Dan to complete the necessary changes to support "function-style" routines, for example...

\Para poner el centro de un cuadro en un punto:

\...which makes "el centro" look to the programmer like just another field in "un cuadro" record,
\and which can be "nested" inside other statements, such as

\Dibujar el centro del cuadro con el color rojo.

\The compiler makes two calls in a case like this (which is why we need Dan to show us how it is done):

\1. A call to the "poner el centro de un cuadro en un punto" function, then
\2. A call to the normal "dibujar un punto con un color" routine.

