\PS. Note that "To decide if a counter is past a number" is not just a simple comparison
\like "To decide if a counter is greater than a number" since it increments the counter
\before checking. So the compound verb "is past" should be special in some way.
A new try out.
A better wording with almost literal translation but ambiguous enough sense could be:
Para decidir si un contador se pasa de un número; \continuous present; it had a sense to check now or to try a modification to the counter and then check
Para decidir si un contador supera un número; \continuous present; same as before
To decide if a counter is past a number:


"está pasado (de)" is also something that has ended the action (verb to be in present but auxiliar verb in past) or "se pasó (de)" aux "se" + verb in past
"se pasa (de)" is a description of right now but is also in pasive voice for Spanish with auxiliar "se" + verb in present

"supera" instead of "superó"
continuous present -it exceeds-  versus past -it exceeded-.

